            			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/4510a6a4547bba49697e9d9a4292f559?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />                    	<p class="comment-details"><em>uf</em> | February 25, 2010 at 1:50 pm</p>
                    		
            		<div class="comment-text">
                    		<p>I am 48, I think I am poor programmer. It is made by beeing graved in old projects and old technologies I must maintain. But I am opened to new technologies and I have learned them. </p>
<p>We old programmers have good habits: </p>
<p>1) We are interested in the problem domain. We want understand it and we are able predict many variants and possibilities. </p>
<p>2) We are used to work deliberately, responsible. We think out several variants to choose the best under given conditions. If we have 4 variants of the solution we know we have to use the sixth one. </p>
<p>3) We study technology and problem domain. Young people would to finish as soon and they are not interested in it. They look up some solution by Google, apply it by copying and rapidly run away. I asked me many times what is better: to finish quick or well?  Nowadays? To be quick. If it needs some changes somebody makes them by the same way.</p>
